&gt; &gt;&gt; &gt; Here. Let us say that I had test classes, Test0, Test1. Each of these
&gt; &gt;&gt; &gt; requires a backend to be configured. I&#39;d like to do something 
&gt; like this:
&gt; &gt;&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt;&gt; &gt; @RunWith(Suite.class)
&gt; &gt;&gt; &gt; @...({Test0.class, Test1.class})
&gt; &gt;&gt; &gt; public abstract class MySuite{
&gt; &gt;&gt; &gt; abstract public void setBackend(Backend backend);
&gt; &gt;&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt;&gt; &gt; @BeforeClass
&gt; &gt;&gt; &gt; public static void doSetup() throws Exception{
&gt; &gt;&gt; &gt; //... stuff to get this all pulled together and configure the tests
&gt; &gt;&gt; &gt; }
&gt; &gt;&gt; &gt; }
&gt; &gt;&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt;&gt; &gt; Then all a tester needs to do is extend the class MySuite, 
&gt; implement the
&gt; &gt;&gt; &gt; method and s/he gets to run their backend against my tests.
&gt; &gt;&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt;&gt; &gt; Complicating factors are that java does not allow for annotations 
&gt; to be
&gt; &gt;&gt; &gt; inherited unless the @interface is created with the @Inherited
&gt; &gt;&gt; &gt; annotation, so attempts to do what is above kick back the message 
&gt; that
&gt; &gt;&gt; &gt; there are no tests to run or some such. At least this is my
&gt; &gt;&gt; &gt; understanding of java annotations...
&gt; &gt;&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt;&gt; &gt; The real life example has not just a couple of test classes, but many
&gt; &gt;&gt; &gt; more that very rigorously exercise the backend. The kludge is to have
&gt; &gt;&gt; &gt; the abstract MySuite class and have the annotations cut and 
&gt; pasted every
&gt; &gt;&gt; &gt; time. This is bad since it will make maintainability problematic (we
&gt; &gt;&gt; &gt; have lots of different backend configurations people want to test
&gt; &gt;&gt; &gt; against). What&#39;s more several people who want to use this really 
&gt; don&#39;t
&gt; &gt;&gt; &gt; know that much about jUnit and we&#39;d really like it to be the case 
&gt; they
&gt; &gt;&gt; &gt; can write a backend then get good feedback on robustness, failure 
&gt; modes,
&gt; &gt;&gt; &gt; you name it.
&gt; &gt;&gt; &gt;
